\name{ICE plot for the alpha-ESF model}
\alias{ice.aesf}
\title{
ICE plot for the \eqn{\alpha}-ESF model
}

\description{
ICE plot for the \eqn{\alpha}-ESF model.
}

\usage{
ice.aesf(be, gama, x, X.esf, ind = 1, frac = 0.25, pos = 0.5)
}

\arguments{
\item{be}{
A numerical matrix with the estimated \eqn{\beta} coefficients of the \eqn{\alpha}-ESF model.
}
\item{gama}{
A numerical matrix with the estimated \eqn{\gamma} coefficients of the \eqn{\alpha}-ESF model.
}
\item{x}{
A numerical matrix with the predictor variables.
}
\item{X.esf}{
A matrix with the values of the eigenvectors computed.
}
\item{ind}{
Which variable to select?.
}
\item{frac}{
Fraction of observations to use. The default value is 0.25.
}
\item{pos}{
This is a number between 0 and 1 and is used to place the legend in the appropriate place.
}
}

\details{
This function implements the Individual Conditional Expecation plots of Goldstein et al. (2015).
See the references for more details.
}

\value{
A graph with several curves, one for each component. The horizontal axis contains the selected variable,
whereas the vertical axis contains the locally smoothed predicted compositional lines.
}

\references{
Tsagris M. and Pantazis Y. (2026). The \eqn{\alpha}--regression for compositional data: a unified framework for standard, temporal and spatial regression models including compositional predictors.
https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.12663

https://christophm.github.io/interpretable-ml-book/ice.html

Goldstein, A., Kapelner, A., Bleich, J. and Pitkin, E. (2015).
Peeking inside the black box: Visualizing statistical
learning with plots of individual conditional expectation.
Journal of Computational and Graphical Statistics 24(1): 44-65.
}

\author{
Michail Tsagris.

R implementation and documentation: Michail Tsagris \email{mtsagris@uoc.gr}.
}

